zed insight**: Addressing statistical heterogeneity in federated learning is crucial for improving model performance and ensuring data privacy.\n\n**Five Core Questions**:\n1. **[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\n   How can we effectively handle statistical heterogeneity in federated learning while ensuring data privacy and scalability?\n\n2. **[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\n   Solving this problem will enhance the robustness and applicability of federated learning in real-world scenarios, particularly in fields like healthcare and data security. It will lead to more accurate models and better privacy protection, which are critical for widespread adoption.\n\n3. **[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\n   Handling statistical heterogeneity requires sophisticated data augmentation techniques that do not compromise privacy. Existing methods often rely on approximations that may not be accurate enough, and naive approaches can lead to data breaches or inconsistent model updates.\n\n4. **[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\n   Previous solutions have struggled with balancing privacy and data utility. They often require raw data exchange or rely on approximations that may not be robust enough for practical applications. Our approach will focus on developing adaptive and privacy-preserving mechanisms that address these limitations.\n\n5. **[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\n   Our approach will involve developing a novel data augmentation technique that uses synthetic data generation methods to smooth data distributions across clients without accessing raw data. We will also design an adaptive learning algorithm that can dynamically adjust to varying data distributions. The methodology will be evaluated using a diverse set of federated learning datasets, and performance will be measured using metrics such as model accuracy, privacy preservation, and computational efficiency. Expected outcomes inc